45Rm 6:1 What should we say, then? Should we go on sinning so that grace may increase - 
45Rm 6:2 Of course not! How can we who died as far as sin is concerned go on living in it? 
45Rm 6:3 Or don't you know that all of us who were baptized into union with the Messiah Jesus were baptized into his death - 
45Rm 6:4 Therefore, through baptism we were buried with him into his death so that, just as the Messiah was raised from the dead by the Father's glory, we too may live an entirely new life.
45Rm 6:5 For if we have become united with him in a death like his, we will certainly also be united with him in a resurrection like his.
45Rm 6:6 We know that our old natures were crucified with him so that our sin-laden bodies might be rendered powerless and we might no longer be slaves to sin.
45Rm 6:7 For the person who has died has been freed from sin. 
45Rm 6:8 Now if we have died with the Messiah, we believe that we will also live with him,
45Rm 6:9 for we know that the Messiah, who was raised from the dead, will never die again; death no longer has mastery over him.
45Rm 6:10 For when he died, he died once and for all as far as sin is concerned. But now that he is alive, he lives for God.
45Rm 6:11 In the same way, you too must continually consider yourselves dead as far as sin is concerned, but living for God through the Messiah Jesus.
45Rm 6:12 Therefore, do not let sin rule your mortal bodies so that you obey their desires.
45Rm 6:13 Stop offering the parts of your body to sin as instruments of unrighteousness. Instead, offer yourselves to God as people who have been brought from death to life and the parts of your body as instruments of righteousness to God.
45Rm 6:14 For sin will not have mastery over you, because you are not under law but under grace.613
45Rm 6:15 What, then, does this mean? Should we go on sinning because we are not under law but under grace? Of course not!
45Rm 6:16 Don't you know that when you offer yourselves to someone as obedient slaves, you are slaves of the one you obey - either of sin, which leads to death, or of obedience, which leads to righteousness - 
45Rm 6:17 But thank God that, though you were once slaves of sin, you became obedient from your hearts to that form of teaching with which you were entrusted!
45Rm 6:18 And since you have been freed from sin, you have become slaves of righteousness. 
45Rm 6:19 I am speaking in simple terms because of the frailty of your human nature. Just as you once offered the parts of your body as slaves to impurity and to greater and greater disobedience, so now, in the same way, you must offer the parts of your body as slaves to righteousness that leads to sanctification.
45Rm 6:20 For when you were slaves of sin, you were "free" as far as righteousness was concerned.
45Rm 6:21 What benefit did you get from doing those things you are now ashamed of? For those things resulted in death.
45Rm 6:22 But now that you have been freed from sin and have become God's slaves, the benefit you reap is sanctification, and the result is eternal life. For the wages of sin is death, but the free gift of God is eternal life in union with the Messiah Jesus our Lord. 
45Rm 7:1 Don't you realize, brothers - for I am speaking to people who know the law - that the law can press its claims over a person only as long as he is alive - 
45Rm 7:2 For a married woman is bound by the law to her husband while he is living, but if her husband dies, she is released from the law concerning her husband.
45Rm 7:3 So while her husband is living, she will be called an adulterer if she lives with another man. But if her husband dies, she is free from this law, so that she is not an adulterer if she marries another man. 
45Rm 7:4 In the same way, my brothers, through the Messiah's body you also died as far as the law is concerned, so that you may belong to another person, the one who was raised from the dead, and may bear fruit for God.
45Rm 7:5 For while we were living according to our human nature, sinful passions were at work in our bodies by means of the law, to bear fruit resulting in death.
45Rm 7:6 But now we have been released from the law by dying to what enslaved us, so that we may serve in the new life of the Spirit, not under the old writings.4
45Rm 7:7 What should we say, then? Is the law sinful? Of course not! In fact, I wouldn't have become aware of sin if it had not been for the law. I wouldn't have known what it means to covet if the law had not said, "You must not covet."
45Rm 7:8 But sin seized the opportunity provided by this commandment and produced in me all kinds of sinful desires, since apart from the law, sin is dead.
45Rm 7:9 At one time I was alive without any connection to the law. But when the rule was revealed, sin sprang to life,
45Rm 7:10 and I died. I found that the very rule that was intended to bring life actually brought death.
45Rm 7:11 For sin, seizing the opportunity provided by the rule, deceived me and used it to kill me.
45Rm 7:12 So then, the law itself is holy, and the rule is holy, just, and good.
45Rm 7:13 Now, did something good bring me death? Of course not! But in order that sin might be recognized as being sin, it used something good to cause my death, so that through the rule, sin might become more exposed as being sinful than ever before.
45Rm 7:14 For we know that the law is spiritual, but I am merely human, sold as a slave to sin.
45Rm 7:15 I don't understand what I am doing. For I don't practice what I want to do, but instead do what I hate.
45Rm 7:16 Now if I practice what I don't want to do, I am admitting that the law is good.
45Rm 7:17 As it is, I am no longer the one who is doing it, but it is the sin that is living in me.
45Rm 7:18 For I know that nothing good lives in me, that is, in my flesh. For I have the desire to do what is right, but I cannot carry it out.
45Rm 7:19 For I don't do the good I want to do, but instead do the evil that I don't want to do.
45Rm 7:20 But if I do what I don't want to do, I am no longer the one who is doing it, but it is the sin that is living in me.719
45Rm 7:21 So I find this to be a principle£º when I want to do what is good, evil is right there with me.
45Rm 7:22 For I delight in the law of God in my inner being,
45Rm 7:23 but I see in my body a different principle waging war with the law in my mind and making me a prisoner of the law of sin that exists in my body.
45Rm 7:24 What a wretched man I am! Who will rescue me from this body that is infected by death - 
45Rm 7:25 Thank God through Jesus the Messiah, our Lord, because with my mind I myself can serve the law of God, even while with my human nature I serve the law of sin.
45Rm 8:1 Therefore, there is now no condemnation for those who are in union with the Messiah Jesus.
45Rm 8:2 For the Spirit's law of life in the Messiah Jesus has set me free from the law of sin and death.
45Rm 8:3 For what the law was powerless to do in that it was weakened by the flesh, God did. By sending his own Son in the form of humanity, he condemned sin by being incarnate,
45Rm 8:4 so that the righteous requirement of the law might be fulfilled in us, who do not live according to human nature but according to the Spirit. 
45Rm 8:5 For those who live according to the flesh set their minds on the things of the flesh, but those who live according to the Spirit set their minds on the things of the Spirit.
45Rm 8:6 To focus our minds on the human nature leads to death, but to focus our minds on the Spirit leads to life and peace.
45Rm 8:7 That is why the mind that focuses on human nature is hostile toward God. It refuses to submit to the authority of God's law because it is powerless to do so.
45Rm 8:8 Indeed, those who are under the control of human nature cannot please God.
45Rm 8:9 You, however, are not under the control of the human nature but under the control of the Spirit, since God's Spirit lives in you. And if anyone does not have the Spirit of the Messiah, he does not belong to him.
45Rm 8:10 But if the Messiah is in you, your bodies are dead due to sin, but the spirit is alive due to righteousness.
45Rm 8:11 And if the Spirit of the one who raised Jesus from the dead is living in you, then the one who raised the Messiah from the dead will also make your mortal bodies alive by his Spirit who lives in you.10
45Rm 8:12 Consequently, brothers, we are not - with respect to human nature, that is - under an obligation to live according to human nature.
45Rm 8:13 For if you live according to human nature, you are going to die, but if by the Spirit you continually put to death the activities of the body, you will live.
45Rm 8:14 For all who are led by God's Spirit are God's children.
45Rm 8:15 For you have not received a spirit of slavery that leads you into fear again. Instead, you have received the Spirit of adoption by whom we cry out, "Abba! Father!" 
45Rm 8:16 The Spirit himself testifies with our spirit that we are God's children.
45Rm 8:17 Now if we are children, we are heirs - heirs of God and co-heirs with the Messiah - if, in fact, we share in his sufferings in order that we may also share in his glory. 
45Rm 8:18 For I consider that the sufferings of this present time are not worth comparing with the glory that will be revealed to us.
45Rm 8:19 For the creation is eagerly awaiting the revelation of God's children,
45Rm 8:20 because the creation has become subject to futility, though not by anything it did. The one who subjected it did so in the certainty
45Rm 8:21 that the creation itself would also be set free from corrupting bondage in order to share the glorious freedom of God's children.
45Rm 8:22 For we know that all the rest of creation has been groaning with the pains of childbirth up to the present time.
45Rm 8:23 However, not only the creation, but we who have the first fruits of the Spirit also groan inwardly as we eagerly await our adoption, the redemption of our bodies.
45Rm 8:24 For we were saved with this hope in mind. Now a hope that can be observed is not really hope, for who hopes for what can be seen - 
45Rm 8:25 But if we hope for what we do not yet observe, we eagerly wait for it with patience.18
45Rm 8:26 In the same way, the Spirit also helps us in our weakness, since we do not know how to pray as we should. But the Spirit himself intercedes for us with groans too deep for words,
45Rm 8:27 and the one who searches our hearts knows the mind of the Spirit, for the Spirit intercedes for the saints according to God's will.
45Rm 8:28 And we know that for those who love God, that is, for those who are called according to his purpose, all things are working together for good.
45Rm 8:29 For those whom he foreknew he also predestined to be conformed to the image of his Son, in order that the Son might be the firstborn among many brothers.
45Rm 8:30 And those whom he predestined, he also called; and those whom he called, he also justified; and those whom he justified he also glorified.827
45Rm 8:31 What, then, can we say about all of this? If God is for us, who can be against us - 
45Rm 8:32 The one who did not spare his own Son, but offered him as a sacrifice for all of us, surely will give us all things, along with his Son, won't he - 
45Rm 8:33 Who shall accuse God's elect? It is God who justifies!
45Rm 8:34 Who is the one to condemn? It is the Messiah Jesus who is interceding on our behalf. He died, and more importantly, has been raised and is seated at the right hand of God. 
45Rm 8:35 Who shall separate us from the Messiah's love? Can trouble, distress, persecution, hunger, nakedness, danger, or a violent death do this - 
45Rm 8:36 As it is written, "For your sake we are being put to death all day long. We are thought of as sheep headed for slaughter."
45Rm 8:37 In all these things we are triumphantly victorious due to the one who loved us.
45Rm 8:38 For I am convinced that neither death, nor life, nor angels, nor rulers, nor things present, nor things to come, nor powers,
45Rm 8:39 nor anything above, nor anything below, nor anything else in all creation can separate us from the love of God that is ours in union with the Messiah Jesus, our Lord.
45Rm 9:1 I am telling the truth because I belong to the Messiah - I am not lying, and my conscience confirms it by means of the Holy Spirit.
45Rm 9:2 I have deep sorrow and unceasing anguish in my heart,
45Rm 9:3 for I could wish that I myself were condemned and cut off from the Messiah for the sake of my brothers, my own people,
45Rm 9:4 who are Israelites. To them belong the adoption, the glory, the covenants, the giving of the law, the worship, and the promises.
45Rm 9:5 To the Israelites belong the patriarchs, and from them, the Messiah descended, who is God over all, the one who is forever blessed. Amen.
45Rm 9:6 Now it is not as though the word of God has failed. For not all Israelites truly belong to Israel,
45Rm 9:7 and not all of Abraham's descendants are his true descendants. On the contrary, "It is through Isaac that descendants will be named for you."
45Rm 9:8 That is, it is not merely the children born through natural descent who were regarded as God's children, but it is the children born through the promise who were regarded as descendants.
45Rm 9:9 For this is the language of the promise£º "At this time I will return, and Sarah will have a son."
45Rm 9:10 Not only that, but Rebecca became pregnant by our ancestor Isaac.
45Rm 9:11 Yet before their children had been born or had done anything good or bad (so that God's plan of election might continue to operate
45Rm 9:12 according to his calling and not by actions), Rebecca was told, "The older child will serve the younger one."
45Rm 9:13 So it is written, "Jacob I loved, but Esau I hated."
45Rm 9:14 What can we say, then? God is not unrighteous, is he? Of course not!
45Rm 9:15 For he says to Moses, "I will be merciful to the person I want to be merciful to, and I will be kind to the person I want to be kind to."
45Rm 9:16 Therefore, God's choice does not depend on a person's will or effort, but on God himself, who shows mercy.
45Rm 9:17 For the Scripture says about Pharaoh, "I have raised you up for this very purpose, to demonstrate my power through you and that my name might be proclaimed in all the earth."
45Rm 9:18 Therefore, God has mercy on whomever he chooses, and he hardens the heart of whomever he chooses.
45Rm 9:19 You may ask me, "Then why does God still find fault with anybody? For who can resist his will?"
45Rm 9:20 On the contrary, who are you - mere man that you are - to talk back to God? Can an object that was molded say to the one who molded it, "Why did you make me like this?"
45Rm 9:21 A potter has the right to do what he wants to with his clay, doesn't he? He can make something for a special occasion or something for ordinary use from the same lump of clay.
45Rm 9:22 Now if God wants to demonstrate his wrath and reveal his power, can't he be extremely patient with the objects of his wrath that are made for destruction - 
45Rm 9:23 Can't he also reveal his glorious riches to the objects of his mercy that he has prepared ahead of time for glory - 
45Rm 9:24 including us, whom he also called, not only from the Jews but from the gentiles as well - 
45Rm 9:25 As the Scripture says in Hosea, "Those who are not my people I will call my people, and the one who was not loved I will call my loved one.
45Rm 9:26 In the very place where it was said to them, 'You are not my people,' they will be called children of the living God."
45Rm 9:27 Isaiah also calls out concerning Israel, "Although the descendants of Israel are as numerous as the grains of sand on the seashore, only a few will be saved.
45Rm 9:28 For the Lord will carry out his plan decisively, bringing it to completion on the earth."
45Rm 9:29 It is just as Isaiah predicted£º "If the Lord of the Heavenly Armies had not left us some descendants, we would have become like Sodom and would have been compared to Gomorrah."
45Rm 9:30 What can we say, then? Gentiles, who were not pursuing righteousness, have attained righteousness, a righteousness that comes through faith.
45Rm 9:31 But Israel, who pursued righteousness based on the law, did not achieve the law.
45Rm 9:32 Why not? Because they did not pursue it on the basis of faith, but as if it were based on achievements. They stumbled over the stone that causes people to stumble.
45Rm 9:33 As it is written, "Look! I am placing a stone in Zion over which people will stumble? a large rock that will make them fall? and the one who believes in him will never be ashamed."
45Rm 10:1 Brothers, my heart's desire and prayer to God about the Jews is that they would be saved.
45Rm 10:2 For I can testify on their behalf that they have a zeal for God, but it is not in keeping with full knowledge.
45Rm 10:3 For they are ignorant of the righteousness that comes from God while they try to establish their own, and they have not submitted to God's means to attain righteousness.
45Rm 10:4 For the Messiah is the culmination of the law as far as righteousness is concerned for everyone who believes. 
45Rm 10:5 For Moses writes about the righteousness that comes from the law as follows£º "The person who obeys these things will find life by them."
45Rm 10:6 But the righteousness that comes from faith says, "Do not say in your heart, 'Who will go up to heaven?' (that is, to bring the Messiah down),
45Rm 10:7 or 'Who will go down into the depths?' (that is, to bring the Messiah back from the dead)."
45Rm 10:8 But what does it say? "The message is near you. It is in your mouth and in your heart." This is the message about faith that we are proclaiming£º
45Rm 10:9 If you declare with your mouth that Jesus is Lord, and believe in your heart that God raised him from the dead, you will be saved.
45Rm 10:10 For one believes with his heart and is justified, and declares with his mouth and is saved.
45Rm 10:11 The Scripture says, "Everyone who believes in him will never be ashamed."
45Rm 10:12 There is no difference between Jew and Greek, because they all have the same Lord, who gives richly to all who call on him. 
45Rm 10:13 "Everyone who calls on the name of the Lord will be saved."
45Rm 10:14 How, then, can people call on someone they have not believed? And how can they believe in someone they have not heard about? And how can they hear without someone preaching - 
45Rm 10:15 And how can people preach unless they are sent? As it is written, "How beautiful are those who bring the good news!"
45Rm 10:16 But not everyone has obeyed the gospel, for Isaiah asks, "Lord, who has believed our message?"
45Rm 10:17 Consequently, faith results from listening, and listening results through the word of the Messiah.14
45Rm 10:18 But I ask, "Didn't they hear?" Certainly they did! In fact, "Their voice has gone out into the whole world, and their words to the ends of the earth."
45Rm 10:19 Again I ask, "Did Israel not understand?" Moses was the first to say, "I will make you jealous by those who are not a nation; I will make you angry by a nation that doesn't understand."
45Rm 10:20 And Isaiah boldly says, "I was found by those who were not looking for me; I was revealed to those who were not asking for me."
45Rm 10:21 But about Israel he says, "All day long I have held out my hands to a disobedient and rebellious people."
45Rm 11:1 So I ask, "God has not rejected his people, has he?" Of course not! I am an Israelite myself, a descendant of Abraham from the tribe of Benjamin.
45Rm 11:2 God has not rejected his people whom he chose long ago. Do you not know what the Scripture says in the story about Elijah, when he pleads with God against Israel - 
45Rm 11:3 "Lord, they have killed your prophets and demolished your altars. I am the only one left, and they are trying to take my life."
45Rm 11:4 But what was the divine reply to him? "I have reserved for myself 7,000 people who have not knelt to worship Baal."
45Rm 11:5 So it is at the present time£º there is a remnant, chosen by grace.
45Rm 11:6 But if this is by grace, then it is no longer on the basis of actions. Otherwise, grace would no longer be grace. 
45Rm 11:7 What, then, does this mean? It means that Israel failed to obtain what it was seeking, but the selected group obtained it while the rest were hardened.
45Rm 11:8 As it is written, "To this day God has put them into deep sleep. Their eyes do not see, and their ears do not hear."
45Rm 11:9 And David says, "Let their table become a snare and a trap, a stumbling block and a punishment for them.
45Rm 11:10 Let their eyes be darkened so that they cannot see, and keep their backs forever bent."
45Rm 11:11 And so I ask, "They have not stumbled so as to fall, have they?" Of course not! On the contrary, because of their stumbling, salvation has come to the gentiles to make the Jews jealous.
45Rm 11:12 Now if their stumbling means riches for the world, and if their fall means riches for the gentiles, how much more will their full participation mean!
45Rm 11:13 I am speaking to you gentiles. Because I am an apostle to the gentiles, I magnify my ministry
45Rm 11:14 in the hope that I can make my people jealous and save some of them.
45Rm 11:15 For if their rejection results in reconciliation of the world, what will their acceptance bring but life from the dead - 
45Rm 11:16 If the first part of the dough is holy, so is the whole batch. If the root is holy, so are the branches. 
45Rm 11:17 Now if some of the branches have been broken off, and you, a wild olive branch, have been grafted in their place to share the rich root of the olive tree,
45Rm 11:18 do not boast about being better than the other branches. If you boast, remember that you do not support the root, but the root supports you.
45Rm 11:19 Then you will say, "Branches were cut off so that I could be grafted in."
45Rm 11:20 That's right! They were broken off because of their unbelief, but you remain only because of faith. Do not be arrogant, but be afraid!
45Rm 11:21 For if God did not spare the natural branches, he certainly will not spare you, either.
45Rm 11:22 Consider, then, the kindness and severity of God£º his severity toward those who fell, but God's kindness toward you - if you continue receiving his kindness. Otherwise, you too will be cut off.
45Rm 11:23 If the Jews do not persist in their unbelief, they will be grafted in again, because God is able to graft them in.
45Rm 11:24 After all, if you were cut off from what is naturally a wild olive tree, and contrary to nature were grafted into a cultivated olive tree, how much easier it will be for these natural branches to be grafted back into their own olive tree!
45Rm 11:25 For I want to let you know about this secret, brothers, so that you will not claim to be wiser than you are£º Stubbornness has come to part of Israel until the full number of the gentiles comes to faith.
45Rm 11:26 In this way, all Israel will be saved, as it is written, "The Deliverer will come from Zion; he will remove ungodliness from Jacob.
45Rm 11:27 This is my covenant with them when I take away their sins."
45Rm 11:28 As far as the gospel is concerned, they are enemies for your sake, but as far as election is concerned, they are loved for the sake of their ancestors.
45Rm 11:29 For God's gifts and calling never change.
45Rm 11:30 For just as you disobeyed God in the past but now have received his mercy because of their disobedience,
45Rm 11:31 so they, too, have now disobeyed. As a result, they may receive mercy because of the mercy shown to you.
45Rm 11:32 For God has locked all people in the prison of their own disobedience so that he may have mercy on them all.
45Rm 11:33 O how deep are God's riches, and wisdom, and knowledge! How unfathomable are his decisions and unexplainable are his ways!
45Rm 11:34 Who has known the mind of the Lord? Or who has become his adviser - 
45Rm 11:35 Or who has given him something only to have him pay it back?"
45Rm 11:36 For all things are from him, by him, and for him. Glory belongs to him forever! Amen. 
45Rm 12:1 I therefore urge you, brothers, in view of God's mercies, to offer your bodies as living sacrifices that are holy and pleasing to God, for this is the reasonable way for you to worship.
45Rm 12:2 Do not be conformed to this world, but continually be transformed by the renewing of your minds so that you may be able to determine what God's will is - what is proper, pleasing, and perfect. 
45Rm 12:3 For by the grace given to me I ask every one of you not to think of yourself more highly than you should think, rather to think of yourself with sober judgment on the measure of faith that God has assigned each of you.
45Rm 12:4 For we have many parts in one body, but these parts do not all have the same function.
45Rm 12:5 In the same way, even though we are many people, we are one body in the Messiah and individual parts connected to each other.
45Rm 12:6 We have different gifts based on the grace that was given to us. So if your gift is prophecy, use your gift in proportion to your faith.
45Rm 12:7 If your gift is serving, devote yourself to serving others. If it is teaching, devote yourself to teaching others.
45Rm 12:8 If it is encouraging, devote yourself to encouraging others. If it is sharing, share generously. If it is leading, lead enthusiastically. If it is helping, help cheerfully.3
45Rm 12:9 Your love must be without hypocrisy. Abhor what is evil; cling to what is good.
45Rm 12:10 Be devoted to each other with mutual affection. Excel at showing respect for each other.
45Rm 12:11 Never be lazy in showing such devotion. Be on fire with the Spirit. Serve the Lord.
45Rm 12:12 Be joyful in hope, patient in trouble, and persistent in prayer.
45Rm 12:13 Supply the needs of the saints. Extend hospitality to strangers. 
45Rm 12:14 Bless those who persecute you. Keep on blessing them, and never curse them.
45Rm 12:15 Rejoice with those who are rejoicing. Cry with those who are crying.
45Rm 12:16 Live in harmony with each other. Do not be arrogant, but associate with humble people. Do not think that you are wiser than you really are. 
45Rm 12:17 Do not pay anyone back evil for evil, but focus your thoughts on what is right in the sight of all people.
45Rm 12:18 If possible, so far as it depends on you, live in peace with all people.
45Rm 12:19 Do not take revenge, dear friends, but leave room for God's wrath. For it is written, "Vengeance belongs to me. I will pay them back, declares the Lord."
45Rm 12:20 But "if your enemy is hungry, feed him. For if he is thirsty, give him a drink. If you do this, you will pile burning coals on his head."
45Rm 12:21 Do not be conquered by evil, but conquer evil with good.
45Rm 13:1 Every person must be subject to the governing authorities, for no authority exists except by God's permission. The existing authorities have been established by God,
45Rm 13:2 so that whoever resists the authorities opposes what God has established, and those who resist will bring judgment on themselves.
45Rm 13:3 For the authorities are not a terror to good conduct, but to bad. Would you like to live without being afraid of the authorities? Then do what is right, and you will receive their approval.
45Rm 13:4 For they are God's servants, working for your good. But if you do what is wrong, you should be afraid, for it is not without reason that they bear the sword. Indeed, they are God's servants to administer punishment to anyone who does wrong.
45Rm 13:5 Therefore, it is necessary for you to be acquiescent to the authorities, not only for the sake of God's punishment, but also for the sake of your own conscience.
45Rm 13:6 This is also why you pay taxes. For rulers are God's servants faithfully devoting themselves to their work.
45Rm 13:7 Pay everyone whatever you owe them - taxes to whom taxes are due, tolls to whom tolls are due, fear to whom fear is due, honor to whom honor is due.6 
45Rm 13:8 Do not owe anyone anything - except to love one another. For the one who loves another has fulfilled the law.
45Rm 13:9 For the commandments, "You must not commit adultery; you must not murder; you must not steal; you must not covet," and every other commandment are summed up in this statement£º "You must love your neighbor as yourself."
45Rm 13:10 Love never does anything that is harmful to its neighbor. Therefore, love is the fulfillment of the law. 
45Rm 13:11 This is necessary because you know the times - it's already time for you to wake up from sleep, because our salvation is nearer now than when we became believers.
45Rm 13:12 The night is almost over, and the day is near. Let's therefore put aside the actions of darkness and put on the armor of light.
45Rm 13:13 Let's behave decently, as people who live in the light of day. No wild parties, drunkenness, sexual immorality, promiscuity, quarreling, or jealousy!
45Rm 13:14 Instead, clothe yourselves with the Lord Jesus, the Messiah, and do not obey your flesh and its desires.1312
45Rm 14:1 Accept anyone who is weak in faith, but not for the purpose of arguing over differences of opinion.
45Rm 14:2 One person believes that he may eat anything, while the weak person eats only vegetables.
45Rm 14:3 The person who eats any kind of food must not ridicule the person who does not eat them, and the person who does not eat certain foods must not criticize the person who eats them, for God has accepted him.
45Rm 14:4 Who are you to criticize someone else's servant? He stands or falls before his own Lord - and stand he will, because the Lord makes him stand.
45Rm 14:5 One person decides in favor of one day over another, while another person decides that all days are the same. Let each one be fully convinced in his own mind£º
45Rm 14:6 The one who observes a special day, observes it to honor the Lord. The one who eats, eats to honor the Lord, since he gives thanks to God. And the one who does not eat, refrains from eating to honor the Lord; yet he, too, gives thanks to God.
45Rm 14:7 For none of us lives for himself, and no one dies for himself.
45Rm 14:8 If we live, we live to honor the Lord; and if we die, we die to honor the Lord. So whether we live or die, we belong to the Lord.
45Rm 14:9 For this reason the Messiah died and returned to life, so that he might become the Lord of both the dead and the living. 
45Rm 14:10 Why, then, do you criticize your brother? Or why do you despise your brother? For all of us will stand before the judgment seat of God.
