58Heb 10:27 but only a terrifying prospect of judgment and a raging fire that will consume the enemies of God.
58Heb 10:28 Anyone who violates the law of Moses dies without mercy "on the testimony of two or three witnesses."
58Heb 10:29 How much more severe a punishment do you think that person deserves who tramples on God's Son, treats as common the blood of the covenant by which it was sanctified, and insults the Spirit of grace - 
58Heb 10:30 For we know the one who said, "Vengeance belongs to me; I will pay them back," and again, "The Lord will judge his people."
58Heb 10:31 It is a terrifying thing to fall into the hands of the living God!30
58Heb 10:32 But you must continue to remember those earlier days, how after you were enlightened you endured a hard and painful struggle.
58Heb 10:33 At times you were made a public spectacle by means of insults and persecutions, while at other times you associated with people who were treated this way.
58Heb 10:34 For you sympathized with the prisoners and cheerfully submitted to the violent seizure of your property, because you know that you have a better and more permanent possession.
58Heb 10:35 So don't lose your confidence, since it holds a great reward for you.
58Heb 10:36 For you need endurance, so that after you have done God's will you can receive what he has promised.
58Heb 10:37 For "in a very little while the one who is coming will return? he will not delay;
58Heb 10:38 but my righteous one will live by faith, and if he turns back, my soul will take no pleasure in him."
58Heb 10:39 Now, we do not belong to those who turn back and are destroyed, but to those who have faith and are saved. 
58Heb 11:1 Now faith is the assurance that what we hope for will come about and the certainty that what we cannot see exists.
58Heb 11:2 By faith our ancestors won approval.
58Heb 11:3 By faith we understand that time was created by the word of God, so that what is seen was made from things that are invisible. 
58Heb 11:4 By faith Abel offered to God a better sacrifice than Cain did, and by faith he was declared to be righteous, since God himself accepted his offerings. And by faith he continues to speak, even though he is dead. 
58Heb 11:5 By faith Enoch was taken away without experiencing death. He could not be found, because God had taken him away. For before he was taken, he won approval as one who pleased God.
58Heb 11:6 Now without faith it is impossible to please God, for whoever comes to him must believe that he exists and that he rewards those who diligently search for him.
58Heb 11:7 By faith Noah, when warned about things not yet seen, reverently prepared an ark to save his family, and by faith he condemned the world and inherited the righteousness that comes by faith. 
58Heb 11:8 By faith Abraham, when called to go to a place he would later receive as his inheritance, obeyed and went, even though he did not know where he was going. 
58Heb 11:9 By faith he made his home in the promised land like a stranger, living in tents, as did Isaac and Jacob, who also inherited the same promise,
58Heb 11:10 because he was waiting for the city with permanent foundations, whose architect and builder is God. 
58Heb 11:11 By faith Sarah, even though she was old and barren, received the strength to conceive, because she was convinced that the one who had made the promise was faithful.
58Heb 11:12 Abraham was as good as dead, yet from this one man came descendants as numerous as the stars in the sky and as countless as the sand on the seashore. 
58Heb 11:13 All these people died having faith. They did not receive the things that were promised, yet they saw them in the distant future and welcomed them, acknowledging that they were strangers and foreigners on earth.
58Heb 11:14 For people who say such things make it clear that they are looking for a country of their own.
58Heb 11:15 If they had been thinking about what they had left behind, they would have had an opportunity to go back.
58Heb 11:16 Instead, they were longing for a better country, that is, a heavenly one. That is why God is not ashamed to be called their God, because he has prepared a city for them. 
58Heb 11:17 By faith Abraham, when he was tested, offered Isaac - he who had received the promises was about to offer his unique son in sacrifice,
58Heb 11:18 about whom it had been said, "It is through Isaac that descendants will be named for you."
58Heb 11:19 Abraham was certain that God could raise the dead, and figuratively speaking, he did get Isaac back in this way. 
58Heb 11:20 By faith Isaac blessed Jacob and Esau in regard to their future. 
58Heb 11:21 By faith Jacob, when he was dying, blessed each of Joseph's sons "and worshiped while leaning on the top of his staff." 
58Heb 11:22 By faith Joseph, when his end was near, spoke about the exodus of the Israelites and gave them instructions about burying his bones. 
58Heb 11:23 By faith Moses was hidden by his parents for three months after he was born, because they saw that he was a beautiful child and were not afraid of the king's order. 
58Heb 11:24 By faith Moses, when he had grown up, refused to be called a son of Pharaoh's daughter,
58Heb 11:25 because he preferred being mistreated with God's people to enjoying the pleasures of sin for a short time.
58Heb 11:26 He thought that being insulted for the sake of the Messiah was of greater value than the treasures of Egypt, because he was looking ahead to his reward. 
58Heb 11:27 By faith he left Egypt, without being afraid of the king's anger, and he persevered because he saw the one who is invisible. 
58Heb 11:28 By faith he established the Passover and the sprinkling of blood to keep the destroyer of the firstborn from touching the people.
58Heb 11:29 By faith they went through the Red Sea as if it were dry land. When the Egyptians tried to do this, they were drowned. 
58Heb 11:30 By faith the walls of Jericho fell down after they had been encircled for seven days. 
58Heb 11:31 By faith Rahab the prostitute did not die with those who were disobedient, because she had welcomed the spies with a greeting of peace. 
58Heb 11:32 And what more should I say? For time would fail me to tell you about Gideon, Barak, Samson, Jephthah, David, Samuel, and the prophets.
58Heb 11:33 Through faith they conquered kingdoms, administered justice, received promises, shut the mouths of lions,
58Heb 11:34 put out raging fires, escaped death by the sword, found strength in weakness, became powerful in battle, and routed foreign armies.
58Heb 11:35 Women received their dead raised back to life. Other people were brutally tortured, but refused to be ransomed, so that they might gain a better resurrection.
58Heb 11:36 Still others endured taunts and floggings, and even chains and imprisonment.
58Heb 11:37 They were stoned to death, sawed in half, and killed with swords. They went around in sheepskins and goatskins. They were needy, oppressed, and mistreated.
58Heb 11:38 The world wasn't worthy of them. They wandered in deserts and mountains, and from caves to holes in the ground. 
58Heb 11:39 All these people won approval for their faith but they did not receive what was promised,
58Heb 11:40 since God had planned something better for us, so that they would not be perfected without us. 
58Heb 12:1 Therefore, having so vast a cloud of witnesses surrounding us, and throwing off everything that hinders us and especially the sin that so easily entangles us, let us keep running with endurance the race set before us,
58Heb 12:2 fixing our attention on Jesus, the pioneer and perfecter of the faith, who, in view of the joy set before him, endured the cross, disregarding its shame, and has sat down at the right hand of the throne of God. 
58Heb 12:3 Think about the one who endured such hostility from sinners, so that you may not become tired and give up.
58Heb 12:4 In your struggle against sin you have not yet resisted to the point of shedding your blood.
58Heb 12:5 You have forgotten the encouragement that is addressed to you as sons£º "My son, do not think lightly of the Lord's discipline or give up when you are corrected by him.
58Heb 12:6 For the Lord disciplines the one he loves, and he punishes every son he accepts."
58Heb 12:7 What you endure disciplines you£º God is treating you as sons. Is there a son whom his father does not discipline - 
58Heb 12:8 Now if you are without any discipline, in which all sons share, then you are illegitimate and not God's sons.
58Heb 12:9 Furthermore, we had earthly fathers who disciplined us, and we respected them for it. We should submit even more to the Father of our spirits and live, shouldn't we - 
58Heb 12:10 For a short time they disciplined us as they thought best, but God does it for our good, so that we may share in his holiness.
58Heb 12:11 No discipline seems pleasant at the time, but painful. Later on, however, for those who have been trained by it, it produces a harvest of righteousness and peace.8
58Heb 12:12 Therefore, strengthen your tired arms and your weak knees,
58Heb 12:13 and straighten the paths of your life, so that your lameness may not become worse, but instead may be healed. 
58Heb 12:14 Pursue peace with everyone, as well as holiness, without which no one will see the Lord.
58Heb 12:15 See to it that no one fails to obtain the grace of God and that no bitter root grows up and causes you trouble, or many of you will become defiled.
58Heb 12:16 No one should be immoral or godless like Esau, who sold his birthright for a single meal.
58Heb 12:17 For you know that afterwards, when he wanted to inherit the blessing, he was rejected because he could not find any opportunity to repent, even though he begged to repent with tears.
58Heb 12:18 You have not come to something that can be touched, to a blazing fire, to darkness, to gloom,
58Heb 12:19 to a trumpet's blast, or to a voice that made the hearers beg that not another word be spoken to them.
58Heb 12:20 For they could not endure the command that was given£º "If even an animal touches the mountain, it must be stoned to death."
58Heb 12:21 Indeed, the sight was so terrifying that Moses said, "I am trembling with fear."
58Heb 12:22 Instead, you have come to Mount Zion, to the city of the living God, to the heavenly Jerusalem, to tens of thousands of angels joyfully gathered together,
58Heb 12:23 to the assembly of the firstborn who are enrolled in heaven, to a judge who is the God of all, to the spirits of righteous people who have been made perfect,
58Heb 12:24 to Jesus, the mediator of a new covenant, and to the sprinkled blood that speaks a better message than Abel's.
58Heb 12:25 See to it that you do not ignore the one who is speaking. For if the hearers did not escape when they ignored the one who warned them on earth, how much less will we escape if we turn away from the one who is from heaven!
58Heb 12:26 At that time his voice shook the earth, but now he has promised, "Once more I will shake not only the earth but also heaven."
58Heb 12:27 The expression "once more" signifies the removal of what can be shaken, that is, what he has made, so that what cannot be shaken may remain.
58Heb 12:28 Therefore, since we are receiving a kingdom that cannot be shaken, let us be thankful and worship God in reverence and fear in a way that pleases him.
58Heb 12:29 For our God is an all-consuming fire. 
58Heb 13:1 Let brotherly love continue.
58Heb 13:2 Stop neglecting to show hospitality to strangers, for by showing hospitality some have had angels as their guests without being aware of it.
58Heb 13:3 Continue to remember those in prison as if you were in prison with them, as well as those who are mistreated, since they also are only mortal.
58Heb 13:4 Let marriage be kept honorable in every way, and the marriage bed undefiled. For God will judge those who commit sexual sins, especially those who commit adultery. 
58Heb 13:5 Keep your lives free from the love of money, and be content with what you have, for God has said, "I will never leave you or abandon you."
58Heb 13:6 Hence we can confidently say, "The Lord is my helper; I will not be afraid. What can anyone do to me?"
58Heb 13:7 Remember your leaders, those who have spoken God's word to you. Think about the impact of their lives, and imitate their faith.
58Heb 13:8 Jesus, the Messiah, is the same yesterday and today - and forever! 
58Heb 13:9 Stop being carried away by all kinds of unusual teachings, for it is good that the heart be strengthened by grace, not by food laws that have never helped those who follow them. 
58Heb 13:10 We have an altar, and those who serve in the tabernacle have no right to eat at it.
58Heb 13:11 For the bodies of animals, whose blood is taken into the sanctuary by the high priest as an offering for sin, are burned outside the camp.
58Heb 13:12 That is why Jesus, in order to sanctify the people by his own blood, also suffered outside the city gate.
58Heb 13:13 Therefore go to him outside the camp and endure the insults he endured.
58Heb 13:14 For here we have no permanent city but are looking for the one that is coming.
58Heb 13:15 Therefore, through him let us always bring God a sacrifice of praise, that is, the fruit of our lips that confess his name.
58Heb 13:16 Do not neglect to do good and to be generous, for God is pleased with such sacrifices.
58Heb 13:17 Continue to obey your leaders and to be submissive to them, for they watch over your souls as those who will have to give a word of explanation. By doing this, you will be letting them carry out their duties joyfully, and not with grief, for that would be harmful for you.
58Heb 13:18 Pray for us, for we are sure that we have a clear conscience and desire to live honorably in every way.
58Heb 13:19 I especially ask you to do this so that I may be brought back to you sooner.
58Heb 13:20 Now may the God of peace, who by the blood of the eternal covenant brought back from the dead our Lord Jesus, the Great Shepherd of the sheep,
58Heb 13:21 equip you with everything good to do his will, accomplishing in us what pleases him through Jesus, the Messiah. To him be glory forever and ever! Amen.
58Heb 13:22 I urge you, brothers, to listen patiently to my encouraging message, for I have written you a short letter.
58Heb 13:23 You should know that our brother Timothy has been set free. If he comes soon, he will be with me when I see you. 
58Heb 13:24 Greet all your leaders and all the saints. Those who are from Italy greet you. 
58Heb 13:25 May grace be with all of you!
